node.text:
This meeting went better than I could have expected. Lark may sound mean in these clips, but the sounds she is making are just her letting Fig know she’s a little uncomfortable and setting some boundaries. After about 30 minutes they spent the rest of the day napping under the couch together. It’s a huge sign of trust to sleep so close to one another! 
-
Can you spot one major difference between them? Notice how much larger Fig is and how much fuller his coat is than hers? Fur farm foxes have been bred to be significantly larger than wild North American foxes.
#larkthefox

node.text: Yesterday Herbal made it through his surgery, but around 9pm his heart stopped. The vets are not exactly sure why he crashed so suddenly, especially after it had been serval hours since he had woken from surgery. My heart aches since he was truly my little buddy. I thought it would be nice to share with all of you the first day I brought him home almost three years ago.

node.text:
After weeks of not being able to find a vet specialized enough to care for Herbal I resorted to making a story begging for help. I was lucky enough to catch the eye of a wonderful vet in Atlanta, Jessica, who was kind enough to walk me through what I needed and pointed me to the Univerity Of Florida Small Mammal Hosptial, where Herbal has been receiving intensive care since Monday. 
-
The staff at UF was able to get him stable, eating, and after a CT scan they were finally able to identify the cause of his issues.
-
Dental disease can be genetic or due to improper care. In Herbal’s case it’s both. Herbal came to me as a neglect case and was fed exclusively hamster food by his previous owner. This poor diet has lead him to where he is now. Chinchilla’s diet needs to be 80% hay to help keep their teeth and digestive tract healthy. Even two years of proper diet and care was not enough to revert the damage that was done by his previous diet. 
-
When adopting an animal please make sure to do proper research on the care that animal requires to be their healthiest. Chinchillas have a lifespan of around 20 years, Herbal is only 3 and will now live with this condition the rest of his life.

node.text:
Newt is quite the character. When he first arrived home, he was so tiny and affectionate. I spent two weeks simply holding him against me everywhere I went, but after his motor skills kicked in so did his personality and I learned quickly that he was not only a sweet and tender boy, but an absolute terrorist.
-
He loves to explore every bit of the world around him. A prime example would be, “Oh look at this toilet, I wonder if I can stick my arm down the hole in there”. He gets into everything and gets extremely riled up when he’s in the mood to play. Which is 18 hours a day. His favorite thing to do is run on the back of the couch and launch himself onto your neck like a raccoon stealth attack. He is five pounds of Velcro goodness and I’m starting to think I’ll never have another moment of peace. Which is just the way I like it.
-
Newt can be very naughty, but he still has a sweet side and cries if he can’t find me. He’s very affectionate and loves to give everyone kisses. I did the math and even though he lost a few points for being a menace turns out he’s still a good boy.

I’ve posted a lot of content of the new babies, but I haven’t really said much about their little personalities. Let’s start with sweet Ferngully.
-
Fern is by far the easiest fox I’ve raised. He’s gentle, intuitive, and very tame. He slept a lot the first few weeks after his arrival and I thought I could attribute his sleepiness to growth spurts, but as time continues to pass it’s more apparent that he’s simply lazy. He is extremely laid back, but when he does have some extra energy to spend he does so by springing around happily. 
-
He’s been a gem to take in public as well. When he arrives at a new place he assesses the environment and then goes to find a spot to nap. He’s happy to be held, loves all other animals, rides peacefully in the car, is not destructive at all, and has me overall in awe of how well behaved he is for a fox. 
He is a blissful bundle of joy and my heart is thankful.

Fig Update: Fig’s surgery was really swift yesterday. It took around an hour. He’s been recovering well and is in good spirits. Because of how bad the break was in his wrist they were unable to repair his leg and the vet suggested to amputate from the break down. So yesterday we said goodbye to Fig’s little hooked foot.
-
I know we’re going to get a lot of questions about what this means as far as him using this leg to walk. I was concerned with leaving the leg as it could cause issues down the road, but at the same time I think this was a way better alternative than amputating the entire leg as that would have been a big adjustment for him. The good news is that he already rarely used this leg. It was more so there for stabilization. Almost like a little kickstand. Thankfully, the loss of another few inches shouldn’t affect him much since he’s already accustomed to walking with three legs. As always I’m going to keep an eye on his progress as he continues to heal and make sure that we do everything we can to give him the best quality of life.
-
Thank you all so much for your well wishes and keeping him in your thoughts yesterday. ♥️

Yesterday afternoon I returned home from being gone a few hours. When I came back I noticed Figs wrist was swollen and he wasn’t using his peg leg, which he will use occasionally when running and for stabilization. I immediately knew something was wrong and I was able to get him in for an emergency visit this morning.
-
Unfortunately my suspicions were correct and his wrist was badly broken. I have no idea how this happened as they are always secure in a safe environment when I’m not home.
-
He’s currently in surgery now. Please keep Figgy in your thoughts today. Sweet boy is stressed and hurting and my heart is sad.
